When individual attribute indicators cannot satisfactorily represent the multidimensional concept, they are compiled into a composite indicator that can measure the complex phenomenon8. It is obvious that the aggregation frameworks and multi-attribute utility functions for individual assessment components can directly affect composite indicator outcomes, although it is also important to appropriately utilize other factors such as proxy variables, normalization methods, weighting methods, etc. Given that weighted and normalized individual attributes are under mutually independent conditions, they can be in general and conventional combined into a composite indicator by either the linear additive utility function7 as:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
